latestPosts.caption: A few years ago I received a DM from @zohrankmamdani. Only recently did I discover its existence. It was a very unusual DM—especially coming from a local assemblyman who would soon be running for higher office. He had very little name recognition at the time, and could have benefited from publicity. But unlike the thousands of messages I’ve received from people with something to promote, Zohran did not ask to be featured on Humans of New York. Instead he asked if he could introduce me to taxi drivers that were struggling beneath the burden of debt. Coming from a man with political ambitions, this self-denying request was so strange as to be almost singular. I don’t endorse politicians on Humans of New York. But I’ll endorse a good man. And it was a good man who cleared 30 minutes from his schedule yesterday to swing by Grand Central to visit Dear New York. Nearly fifty student artists were visiting that day with their families, and I thought a surprise visit from this widely-loved future mayor would be a special memory for all of them. Before Zohran’s arrival I was convinced I’d made a terrible mistake. The Vanderbilt Hall exhibit was filled to capacity with adult visitors. Dear New York is self-funded so there was very little staff and security for crowd control. In the crush of people I was almost certain this special day for the kids would devolve into thirty minutes of selfie requests. But everyone rose to the occasion. Hundreds of adults quickly cleared the room and stood outside the exhibit. Eleven very notable adult artists are also featured in the exhibition, but even they took a step back, so that these students could briefly have the stage to themselves. Each child stood by their work and Zohran was able to meet all of them, one at a time, and honor their contributions to the most-visited art show in New York City. Thanks to everyone who ceded the stage yesterday to make this moment possible. Thank you Zohran for literally sitting down on the floor so that these young artists could feel so tall. Thank you for continually centering other people in your life and work. And thank you, for being such an important part of Dear New York.

latestPosts.caption: Dear New York closes on October 19th. It’s been the honor and joy of my life to see this take flight. It’s been a magical six days of community and connection, and we have some extra special moments coming in the final week. Thanks to all of you who have made the pilgrimage to Grand Central these last few days. And I hope to see many more of you as the clock ticks down to the closing ceremony next Sunday.  Note: The Vanderbilt Hall exhibit is closed today for a prescheduled event, but will reopen tomorrow and remain open until the conclusion of the installation.

“We were driving to Atlanta to see my parents when I got a text from their mother. It said: ‘I moved to Chicago.’ When we got back to New York, her stuff was gone. We’d been going through a rough patch, but in my opinion—nothing that couldn’t be fixed. No infidelity or anything like that. She’s an artist too. I guess she’s on a journey to find herself. My parents offered to take the kids in Georgia, so that option was on the table. But I thought: ‘Imagine what their life will be like if they lose both of you.’ The first month was rough. Catastrophic. But I took a step back. I thought: ‘You still have the kids. She’s not contesting. A lot of people don’t have family, so start there. And don’t squander what you have.’ Before COVID I’d been the manager of a huge market: a whole bunch of people. And I didn’t love them, so I figured managing four kids would be easier than that. As a manager I learned to ask my employees to communicate what they’re going to do. Ask them what part they’re going to play. And if they understand what happens if they don’t do their part. So I did the same thing with the kids. It ended up becoming a collective project. My role is to make sure that we’re not out in the street, the lights are on, and we have food in the fridge. Everyone cleans. Everyone does their schoolwork. Libby helps with the twins’ hair. My son handles the garbage and the heavier things. The twins need to listen to their big sister. It’s a whole checks and balances thing. They never embarrass me when I take them places. Not because they’re worried about losing things, but because I taught them that they represent me. We’ve made it three years now. I felt happy on New Years; it’s just a reminder— we pushed through another year.’ My goal is to get them through these next six years with as little harm as possible. They have their own dreams: Libby wants to be an artist, my son is a musician, one of the twins wants to be a train engineer, the other wants to go into the medical field. I never want them to say: ‘We could have done this, but Mom left.’ So that’s my goal: for them to be able to do all those things, despite our challenges. That’s the reason I’m going so hard.”

latestPosts.caption: “I was a happy child from about five to seven. That’s when we got taken from our mother and sent to live with our aunt. I remember waking up on Christmas, snow on the ground, my uncle outside hanging up lights. Beautiful memories. But at one point it all stopped, and after that I just remember screaming. My uncle would scare me to the point where I’d piss myself. He was never satisfied until that happened. My aunt tried to stand up for me. Whenever my uncle said: ‘That’s not my son,’ she’d tell him: ‘We decided to do this.’ But eventually he stopped loving her too and after that the hatred was coming from everywhere. I tried to suicide myself before I knew what suicide was. But I made it through. I’ve been on my own now since the age of nineteen and haven’t been evicted once. I wish I drank less. But I’ve been strong, I’ve been working. I hang around with people older than me and they don’t necessarily have something of their own. They see me, and they’re like, ‘You’re ill. You’re getting up and going to work every day. You’re holding it down.’ But am I happy? I’ve experienced glimpses of happiness, but I’ve never been truly happy. I still battle a lot of things. The other day I woke up screaming, like fuck! But I’ve got to be here for something. I have a friend named Dre; he knows things about me, and he says: ‘For you to still be here— you’re here for a reason. You’ve got to see it through to the end— to find out what it all means.’ What I’d really love is to finally have some freedom one day. Not having to think about what I’m going to eat tomorrow, things like that. I feel like it’s coming at some point. And when it does, I’m going straight back to my aunt and uncle. No anger, nothing. Because I want them to be free too. They were also abused, mind you. They showed me the marks. My aunt also tried to commit suicide. They were never happy. They were never free. But they tried their hardest to survive. They still tried for me, I know that. And if I ever get some freedom, if I ever get some happiness, I want them to feel it too.”

latestPosts.caption: “I’m 66 now. I’m looking at the end of this journey and I don’t have time for bullshit. We are mission-specific here, no fluff. The life expectancy for kids in this community is a decade less than my own kids’. And it’s a very unhealthy, medically-induced life. It’s a function of the environment; in this neighborhood there are twenty-nine pharmacies, fifty-five fast food restaurants, and not a single supermarket. But environment can be changed. I started Harlem Grown fourteen years ago by turning an abandoned junkyard into an urban farm— just to give kids a safe space and teach them about nutrition. But things started happening on the periphery: the kids’ parents would come hang out, and sometimes I’d send them home with fresh food from the farm: a few herbs, some tomatoes. I thought it was cute at first, but people heard we were giving out food and started showing up. Since then we’ve just kept ramping up. We have fourteen farms now. We’ve tried to stay true to our niche of providing fresh, nutritious, healthy foods: fruits and vegetables in particular. With the help of our partners, last year we were able to give away 160,000 pounds of food. I can regurgitate this shit, but when we get to the personal points man, it just fucks me up. Twenty-three kids from our program became the first in their family to attend four-year colleges. The first girl who ever joined our program is pursuing her PhD. Where would she be without that intervention? That’s my terror. Imagine if we weren’t here, how worse it would be for so many. When I started this, I was just looking for a volunteer opportunity. In my mind I was killing time while figuring out my next move. But the kids became my next move. You meet these kids, and you learn about their lives, and what are you supposed to do? When you don’t know about something— you can claim you just don’t know. But once you do know, what do you do? Harlem Grown grew from one tiny, little lot that we called a farm to something that has been able to create so much joy and opportunity. It wasn’t money that did that. It was time. I had time, and we all have time. But time for what? And that’s what we have to ask ourselves.”

latestPosts.caption: “All advertising directed at women says: ‘You’re not good enough.’ With men it’s a little different. The message is: ‘You’re great, but you can be even greater.’ That’s why I’m always going to have a chip on my shoulder against capitalism. There’s this scarcity mentality: eighteen people have all the money, and there isn’t enough to go around, so the rest of us have to compete with each other for scraps. The whole thing is based on this idea of competing with your fellow man. It’s one of the big reasons I created The Free Store. To show that there’s this undercurrent of kindness and camaraderie that also motivates people, and it has nothing to do with competition. I opened the first location during the height of the pandemic; things were really dark. Everyone was leaving New York and going back to Ohio or Connecticut or wherever the fuck they’re from, and they’re just leaving their belongings on the street. All this valuable stuff, just sitting on the street. It’s like: ‘What the fuck?’ So I hung up some shelves on one of these boarded-up buildings, stocked them with perfectly good stuff from the street, and hung up a sign that said: ‘Free Store.’ I ended up opening seventeen locations. I’m proud of it, I’m very proud of it. The Free Store had no owners, no managers, no customers. Only participants. Just people being people. There were a few motherfuckers, but almost everyone took only what they needed. Nobody was guarding these shelves, and for the most part they were always stacked with good stuff. I think it challenged this whole scarcity mindset, and it proved that even in the darkest times we will always have enough. It’s been my experience that when people see just how much stuff there is, the less likely they are to hoard everything. And the more faith they’ll have in, like, their fellow man.”

latestPosts.caption: “I love him, but he was a very tough dad. He was something called a txiv geej; it’s a very respected position in our culture. At funerals he would play an instrument called a geej; it looks like a long flute with six smaller flutes attached. And its song is supposed to help the spirit pass on to the next world. My dad wanted nothing more than for his sons to continue the tradition. He’d make us practice for hours every day. When we were kids it was kinda cool. We’d play at Hmong New Year celebrations, and everyone would watch, and they’d be very polite. But as we became teenagers, it was like—this is not cool. We were living in a small town in Wisconsin— not a lot of Asian folks in general. I was focused on trying to get by every day. I just wanted to hang out. I guess you could say I became more American. We had so many arguments over it, there was a lot of: ‘I don’t understand. This isn’t why we brought you to the States, not for this.’ I was very hurt by it; obviously you want your dad to be proud of you. But he was very hurt by it too—that he didn’t have a son who was observing the religion, playing the instrument, following his footsteps. It might sound like he was being selfish, but I think it was more selfless than selfish. He thought that if I didn’t follow the religion—our spirits would go two different places. It’s what he truly believed. And he wanted me to follow his footsteps after death as well. But toward the end of his life, he finally told me: ‘You’re a dad now. You’ve become your own man, and I respect whatever path you choose to follow.’ And I was so thankful for that. At his funeral one of his best friends played the geej. My father left a recording of exactly how he wanted it played; it’s almost as if he was providing the exact coordinates of where he wanted his soul to be.”

latestPosts.caption: “My mother had a lot of different men in and out. People would come live with us. We were always moving around. I counted the places we lived at one point, and it was over twenty-five. It was chaos, emotional chaos. The not knowing where you’re going to live, not knowing if you’re going to be able to eat. Not knowing clearly what the fuck is actually going on. I moved out and got my own apartment when I turned sixteen. Went to Job Corps, finished Job Corps. Got my GED. By the time I was seventeen I was living by myself, going to college, I had a job. I was meeting a lot of people I would otherwise have never met. I’m proud of myself. I’m living up to my own standard. I made it through all this bullshit. I had enough power to do it. I had enough talent to do it. I felt like a super independent woman. There’s a joy of doing things on your own: the freedom, the not having to answer to anyone. Nobody you have to call and say: ‘Hey, it’s me. This is where I’m going, this is what I’m doing, this is when I’m going to be home.’ There’s also a pain of doing it on your own—and it happens to be that exact same thing.”

latestPosts.caption: “I’m feeling a sense of being completely blindsided by the issues of the world because everything was working out for me. In our political philosophy class we’re learning about this guy, John Rawls. And he talks about how whether you’re rich or poor, and even really if you’re talented or talentless—it has nothing to do with you. It’s arbitrary. So much of your life is shaped by the position you’re born into. And I happen to have had a really lucky roll of the dice. I had, like, great parents. I lived in an apartment on the Upper West Side. I went to a private school where I got to call my teachers by their first names. I had wonderful friends, cute dogs, nice vacations. I had the greatest roll of the dice ever. Yet I walk five paces outside of my front door, and I’ll see someone who had a shit roll: sleeping on the streets, just trying to survive. It’s like: what did I do to deserve this? Nothing. I could easily just fade into the background and do whatever is great for myself and my family. I don’t think anyone would notice, or blame me. Not everyone needs to change the world. My girlfriend didn’t have as much privilege as me, and she is very focused on her dream of owning a house. I think that’s wonderful. I hope she accomplishes that, and I can live with her in that house one day. But I’ve lived in a house. I’ve lived a lavish life. I’ve had a lot of pleasure, I’ve had a lot of joy. I don’t need to constantly pursue that, you know. I’d love to try my best to use this ‘everything working out for me’ to do something for someone else.”

latestPosts.caption: “We stayed together for two years and realized that we were probably better off as friends than as a couple. Our daughter was two at the time. It was horrible. One day you have access to your child 24/7, and it’s all you’ve known. Then the next day it’s split in half and it’s not always controlled by you. You’re living across the street, but you’re still trying to be the protector. I just didn’t want any trauma. That was the big thing for me: no trauma. Because I grew up with it. I never wanted her emotionally needing me, crying herself to sleep: ‘Daddy, daddy, daddy.’ And to my knowledge she never has. For me it was about consistency: always showing up, never being late. And staying friends with her mother. That was very important to me. After the initial split I remember it was about sixty weeks in a row of me suggesting to my ex: let’s all go to dinner, let’s all go to dinner. Finally she said yes, and it’s become something we’ve done regularly for the past ten years. Our daughter is twelve now, and we all had dinner the other night. We talked about what’s going on at school. We joked about things. I like to think from the outside we looked like any nuclear family out to dinner. I just think it’s so important for our daughter to consistently see the two of us, being our natural selves, in the presence of each other. I’m not the perfect father. And she’s not the perfect mother. We have different parenting styles, and we disagree on a lot of things. But I don’t think we’ve ever been jerks to each other. My ex would always cover for me if I travelled, and I travel a lot, because I work for a Swedish paper mill. I know it was hard for her a lot of times. But if she asked me to cover a weekend, even if I had other plans, I’d agree. And we’ve never used access as a weapon. Even if we were in the middle of a disagreement—we both had access to our daughter every day. We would never say: ‘This isn’t your day’ or ‘This isn’t your week.’ Technically it’s not my week right now, but I’m on the way to pick up my daughter from school. I’m going to take her for a quick snack, and then I’m going to drop her off at her mom’s.”

latestPosts.caption: “Ten years ago I met a professional flower girl. She was 24-years old. She was going through a tough time, so my husband and I tried to help her. We let her use this space. We laid out all the money: transportation, allowance, everything. I worked alongside her in the shop. But the flower girl, she always party. She took the $3,000 I gave her and disappeared. It’s OK. She was young, whatever. We were going to close the shop, but my husband said: ‘You are always happy when you are here, why don’t you run it yourself?’ So that’s what I did. I used to be a fashion designer, so I’m very good with color. I know composition naturally. And also— everything I touch, it grows. People think it’s a miracle. It’s not a miracle. It’s just a matter of caring. When your customer authorizes you to do something, do the best you can offer. People are not dumb. They can see how much thought and time you put into your work. They can tell if you are like crocodile, doing as little as possible, trying to eat all the money you can. Look at all the shops up and down the street—you can see who puts their heart into it. Look at the plants in front of the store. If the plants are dying, the business is dying. It’s a matter of caring. You must care for everything around you. First, I take care of myself. That is most important. I’m seventy-one. If my muscles feel pain, I stop. I’ll do my stretching. Then I care for my husband. He’s a very good partner. Two years ago he had a stroke; he has some minor health things still. So I care for him. We adopted two little kitties. We make them delicious food like human food: turkey, chicken, fish. They grow very big. We take good care of them. Then we care for our friends, our customers, even our customer’s dogs. If you treat your customers’ dogs well, they will smell you and remember you. Everything is together: plants, animals, humans. If you care, you will grow. But not enough people care. It’s not that they aren’t smart. It’s that they want to try everything, so they never care enough about any one thing. Too many choices. Me? This is my only choice. Come by anytime, I’m around.”
